    "instruction": "For only these candidate services: carts, catalogue, orders, payment, user, do the following and return compact tables (limit 20 rows):\n1) Metric fault table: Using metric.csv, compute global P95 and P05 for each (cmdb_id,kpi_name) using the full series. Then filter metric rows to the incident window [2024-01-18 20:21:16 UTC .. 2024-01-18 20:51:16 UTC]. For each (cmdb_id,kpi_name) produce: p95, p05, count_in_window, count_high_anoms (value >= p95), first_high_ts (earliest), count_low_anoms (value <= p05), first_low_ts, max_in_window, min_in_window, and a numeric severity estimate defined as (max_in_window - p95)/max(1e-9, p95) for high-side anomalies (use NaN if p95==0). Return rows where count_high_anoms>0 or count_low_anoms>0. Sort by (count_high_anoms+count_low_anoms) desc then severity desc. Columns: cmdb_id,kpi_name,p95,p05,count_in_window,count_high_anoms,first_high_ts,count_low_anoms,first_low_ts,max_in_window,min_in_window,severity. Limit to top 50 rows but only needs to return up to 20.\n2) Log summary: Using log.csv filtered to the same incident window, aggregate per cmdb_id the sum of values for log.error_count and log.row_count (if present), the count of log rows for that cmdb_id, and the earliest timestamp where log.error_count>0. Return one row per candidate cmdb_id with columns: cmdb_id, sum_log_error_count, sum_log_row_count, log_row_count, first_nonzero_error_ts. If a log metric is missing for a cmdb_id, return 0/NaN accordingly.\nKeep outputs compact, do not print full raw series, and limit row counts as requested."
